Basic Logistic Regression Model predicting heart failure based on demographics (age, sex), body composition (BMI), and pollution exposures (no2 and pm25):¶

merged_pheno_env: phenotype + pollution (clean), merged_pheno_env_no_na: complete-case version, merged_all: phenotype + pollution + proteomics (original, not complete-case)

This logistic regression model, using complete-case data from phenotype and pollution variables, shows that age, sex, BMI, and PM₂.₅ are significant predictors of heart failure. NO₂ was not significantly associated. Each unit increase in PM₂.₅ exposure was associated with a 13% increase in the odds of heart failure, while BMI had a stronger effect (76% increase per unit). Sex and age were also highly significant. The model fit is reasonable based on AIC (13,948), and residuals suggest the presence of a few outliers.

This logistic regression model includes participants with partially missing data, allowing for greater sample retention compared to the complete-case version. Using na.exclude, only participants missing specific model variables (e.g., PM₂.₅ or BMI) were excluded, while others—particularly those with valid NO₂ data—were retained. The model confirms that age, sex, BMI, and PM₂.₅ are significant predictors of heart failure. Notably, the coefficient for PM₂.₅ was larger than in the complete-case model, indicating a 4.5x increase in odds of heart failure per unit increase in PM₂.₅ exposure (exp(1.50) ≈ 4.49). NO₂ remained non-significant in both models. Overall model fit was comparable (AIC = 13,949) to the complete-case model, despite including ~36,000 additional participants.

This model incorporated phenotype, air pollution, and proteomic data while preserving participants with partial missingness via na.exclude. A total of 7,277 observations were excluded, leaving ~38,000 participants. Significant predictors of heart failure included age, sex, BMI, and IL-6, with IL-6 showing a notably strong positive association (p < 0.001, OR ≈ 1.43). Neither NO₂ nor PM₂.₅ were significant in this model, suggesting that once proteomic biomarkers are included, their effect may be attenuated or explained by downstream inflammation pathways. Similarly, SOD1 and SOD2 were not significant predictors in this model. The overall model fit was strong, with a reduced AIC of 1901.4, indicating improvement over previous models despite the smaller sample size.

This logistic regression model includes participants with complete data across phenotype, pollution, and proteomics variables (~37,959 participants). As in the previous model, age, sex, BMI, and IL-6 were statistically significant predictors of heart failure. Across four logistic regression models, we found that adding proteomic markers significantly improved predictive performance for heart failure. This expanded model evaluated the contribution of additional pollution and phenotype variables in predicting heart failure. While age, sex, body fat percentage, and IL-6 remained strong predictors, none of the pollution variables reached statistical significance, including NO₂, NOₓ, PM₂.₅, and PM₂.₅ absorbance. The inclusion of multiple air quality measures may introduce multicollinearity or dilute individual effects, especially given their correlation. Surprisingly, BMI and waist circumference were not significant, likely due to shared variance with body fat percent, which remained significant. The model’s AIC increased slightly compared to a simpler model, suggesting limited improvement from adding all variables.

VIF (Variance Inflation Factor) and stepwise model selection:¶

to help detect multicollinearity and find a better performing model for this dataset

merged_all_no_na (Phenotype + Pollution + Proteomics, Complete Case)¶

In [8]:
# Manual VIF function (This version of R doesn't allow me to use certain libraries with this function)
vif_manual <- function(model) {
  vifs <- NULL
  vars <- names(coef(model))[-1]
  for (var in vars) {
    f <- as.formula(paste(var, "~", paste(vars[vars != var], collapse = "+")))
    r2 <- summary(lm(f, model$data))$r.squared
    vif <- 1 / (1 - r2)
    vifs <- c(vifs, vif)
  }
  names(vifs) <- vars
  return(vifs)
}

VIF analysis showed that some variables in the model are highly correlated. NO₂ had the highest VIF (12.2), suggesting strong overlap with NOₓ (VIF = 7.7), which makes sense since both come from traffic-related pollution. Moderate multicollinearity was also seen between BMI, waist circumference, and body fat percent, which all measure body size and composition. On the other hand, age and the proteomic biomarkers (SOD1, SOD2, IL-6) had very low VIFs, meaning they aren’t redundant. These results suggest that we could simplify the model by removing either NO₂ or NOₓ, and keeping just one body composition variable — likely body fat percent, since it was consistently significant.

# Create an ROC curve

pred_probs <- predict(model_final_all, type = "response")
true_labels <- df_all_no_na$disease

# Create a data frame with predictions and actual values
roc_data <- data.frame(
  prob = pred_probs,
  actual = true_labels
)

# Sort by predicted probabilities
roc_data <- roc_data[order(-roc_data$prob), ]

# Initialize TPR and FPR
tpr <- c()
fpr <- c()
thresholds <- unique(roc_data$prob)

P <- sum(roc_data$actual == 1)
N <- sum(roc_data$actual == 0)

for (thresh in thresholds) {
  tp <- sum(roc_data$prob >= thresh & roc_data$actual == 1)
  fp <- sum(roc_data$prob >= thresh & roc_data$actual == 0)
  tpr <- c(tpr, tp / P)
  fpr <- c(fpr, fp / N)
}


ggplot(data.frame(FPR = fpr, TPR = tpr), aes(x = FPR, y = TPR)) +
  geom_line(color = "steelblue", linewidth = 1.2) +  # <- changed from size to linewidth
  geom_abline(linetype = "dashed", color = "gray") +
  labs(
    title = "ROC Curve (Manual)",

    y = "True Positive Rate"

# Calculate the AUC
# Function to calculate AUC using trapezoidal rule
calc_auc <- function(fpr, tpr) {
  # Ensure FPR is sorted (just in case)
  ord <- order(fpr)
  fpr <- fpr[ord]
  tpr <- tpr[ord]
  
  # Trapezoidal rule
  auc <- sum(diff(fpr) * (head(tpr, -1) + tail(tpr, -1)) / 2)
  return(auc)
}

# Calculate AUC
auc_manual <- calc_auc(fpr, tpr)
print(paste("AUC:", round(auc_manual, 4)))

# Get model coefficients and confidence intervals
coef_df <- summary(model_final_all)$coefficients
confint_df <- confint(model_final_all)

# Create tidy data frame with odds ratios
forest_df <- data.frame(
  Variable = rownames(coef_df),
  OR = exp(coef_df[, "Estimate"]),
  LowerCI = exp(confint_df[, 1]),
  UpperCI = exp(confint_df[, 2]),
  p_value = coef_df[, "Pr(>|z|)"]
)

# Add significance label
forest_df$Significant <- ifelse(forest_df$p_value < 0.05, "Yes", "No")

# Remove intercept
forest_df <- forest_df[forest_df$Variable != "(Intercept)", ]

# Plot using ggplot2
library(ggplot2)

ggplot(forest_df, aes(x = reorder(Variable, OR), y = OR, color = Significant)) +
  geom_point(size = 3) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = LowerCI, ymax = UpperCI), width = 0.2) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 1, linetype = "dashed", color = "gray") +

  scale_y_log10() +
  labs(

Does air pollution exposure increase IL-6 expression?¶

I want to see if air pollution via PM2.5, NO2, and NOx is known to trigger systemic inflammation. IL-6 is a key inflammatory cytokine that we now know based on our tests plays a role in cardiovascular disease. I'm going to use linear regression here since IL-6 is not a binary variable.

PM2.5 has a statistically significant positive association where higher exposure correlates with increased IL-6 expression which could support the hypothesis that air pollution may activate inflammatory pathways linked to cardiovascular risks.

My other air pollution covariates NO2 and NOx showed no significance in this particular model.

Age, sex, and body fat % also have strong and highly significant positive effects on IL-6 which seemed to be a likely correlation (IL-6 increases with aging, adiposity, and is differing in sexes) giving me some confidence in my model. My model fit here is 0.177 which is a modest score but pretty on par for biological data.

Calculate the R2 of PM2.5 to find the unique variance in IL-6 expression explained by PM2.5.¶

To do this manually I need to create a reduced model without PM2.5 then subtract the R2 of the reduced model from the full model to find PM2.5 R2.

In [32]:
# Calculate the semi-partial R2 of PM2.5 manually
# Reduced model without PM2.5
model_no_pm25 <- lm(il6_rint ~ no2 + nox + age + sex + body_fat_percent,
                    data = df_all_no_na)

# Partial R² for PM2.5
r2_full <- summary(model_il6_pollution)$r.squared
r2_reduced <- summary(model_no_pm25)$r.squared
partial_r2_pm25 <- r2_full - r2_reduced

partial_r2_pm25
0.000257946321507357

This means that PM2.5 explains only about 0.026% of the variation in IL-6 expression. So although it has a statistically significant effect it's practical effect size on IL-6 is quite small in terms of variance explanied.

IL-6 is more strongly driven by sex, age, or % fat.
